    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** - May 7, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🚀 Anthropic rented the Musk compute bunker and called it capacity planning\n\nThe Claude shortage apparently needed a plot twist with rockets in the appendix.\n\n- **The deal:** SpaceXAI says Anthropic will access Colossus 1, with more than 220,000 Nvidia GPUs across H100, H200 and GB200 systems.\n- **The fix:** Reuters says the agreement adds more than 300 megawatts within a month, with Anthropic raising Claude Pro, Max, Team, Enterprise and Claude Code limits.\n- **The sequel:** both sides are already flirting with multi-gigawatt orbital AI compute.\n\n*Cloud strategy has become land, power, cooling and maybe low Earth orbit. Normal industry behavior, clearly.*\n\n**Sources:** [xAI](https://x.ai/news/anthropic-compute-partnership) | [Reuters via Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/anthropic-signs-deal-with-spacex-for-ai-supercomputer-access-4664461)\n\n---\n\n## 🕸️ OpenAI made GPU traffic a standards problem\n\nThe model race has found another glamorous bottleneck: packets getting lost in very expensive rooms.\n\n- **The protocol:** OpenAI released Multipath Reliable Connection through the Open Compute Project with AMD, Broadcom, Intel, Microsoft and Nvidia.\n- **The target:** MRC is designed for large training clusters, using multipath networking and source routing to improve resilience and reduce wasted GPU time.\n- **The scale:** OpenAI says ChatGPT now has more than 900 million weekly users, which makes network plumbing an existential product feature.\n\n*The future of intelligence is apparently a routing table with better manners.*\n\n**Sources:** [OpenAI](https://openai.com/index/mrc-supercomputer-networking/) | [AMD](https://www.amd.com/en/blogs/2026/amd-advances-ai-networking-at-scale-with-mrc.html)\n\n---\n\n## 📚 Publishers put Zuckerberg personally in the Llama copyright dock\n\nThe AI training data fight has moved from abstract principle to CEO named defendant. Efficient escalation.\n\n- **The suit:** AP reports Elsevier, Cengage, Hachette, Macmillan, McGraw Hill and author Scott Turow sued Meta and Mark Zuckerberg in Manhattan federal court.\n- **The claim:** plaintiffs say Meta used millions of copyrighted books and journal articles to train Llama without permission or payment.\n- **The hook:** the complaint alleges Zuckerberg personally authorized and encouraged the conduct, turning fair-use theory into executive-liability theater.\n\n*Move fast and break things remains less charming when the thing is the evidence file.*\n\n**Sources:** [AP](https://apnews.com/article/meta-mark-zuckerberg-ai-publishers-lawsuit-llama-5609846d4d840014974a847b01079c32) | [Reuters via Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/major-publishers-sue-meta-for-copyright-infringement-over-ai-training-4659515)\n\n---\n\n## 🧾 Coinbase made layoffs sound like an org chart prompt\n\nAI is now the sentence executives put between market pressure and severance paperwork.\n\n- **The cut:** Axios says Coinbase will lay off about 700 workers and rebuild around AI-native pods and talent.\n- **The caveat:** Armstrong also cited crypto volatility, while Axios notes many companies are tying cuts to AI without clear productivity metrics.\n- **The pattern:** Coinbase joins Block, Pinterest and Shopify in presenting automation as both operating model and headcount argument.\n\n*The agents are here. Conveniently, so is the restructuring memo.*\n\n**Sources:** [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/05/06/ai-layoff-coinbase) | [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/05/coinbase-to-lay-off-14-of-staff-as-part-of-broader-restructuring/)\n\n---\n\n## 💼 Claude got banker plugins, because pitchbooks were not going to automate themselves\n\nFinancial services asked for productivity. Anthropic heard: please embed the model inside every spreadsheet-shaped anxiety.\n\n- **The launch:** Anthropic released ten ready-to-run finance agent templates for pitchbooks, KYC screening and month-end close.\n- **The desktop grab:** Claude now works across Excel, PowerPoint and Word, with Outlook support coming soon.\n- **The benchmark:** Anthropic says Claude Opus 4.7 leads Vals AI's Finance Agent benchmark at 64.37%.\n\n*Wall Street automation is not replacing the deck. It is making the deck reproduce faster.*\n\n**Sources:** [Anthropic](https://www.anthropic.com/news/finance-agents?cam=claude) | [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/05/05/anthropic-wall-street-dimon-amodei)\n"
  }
]
